text: We couldn't explore the concept of #WhatIsFashionNow without talking to @rachaelwangstudio. Black trans women's lives matter — not just when we are protesting in the streets — but also on the cover of magazines. Read their cover stories at the link in bio. #WhatIsFashionNow

text:
August 18 marks the 100th anniversary of the ratification of the 19th Amendment — a celebrated milestone in the United States’ story of suffrage and of equal rights for women. But because of sexism immigration bans and a patchwork of other discriminatory state laws Native Black Asian and Latinx women were barred from voting well into the 20th century; even now many Americans of all gender identities remain unrepresented. For our August cover Teen Vogue is elevating the stories of women of color who have been disenfranchised and often written out of history but remain committed to a decades-long struggle to carve out a place in our imperfect democracy 💫

At the link in bio writer and activist @raquel_willis actor @jess_m_garcia Puerto Rican feminist blogger Aliana Margarita Bigio Alcoba (@con.sentimientopr) actor @leahmlewis @flrightsrestore’s Tiniesha Johnson Representative @ayannapressley Native Alaskan student activist @charitieropati actor and activist @yarashahidi @NYCCouncil candidate @shahanafrombk and @blklivesmatter activist @thandiweabdullah weigh in on what voter suppression has looked like in their communities why voting must be accompanied by vigorous on-the-ground organizing and on the complex meanings of this anniversary. #TheUncounted 📸: @toryrust + @kaibyrd_

text: It's July you say? Well the good thing is that #Pride can (and should) be a year-round celebration 💖 For Teen Vogue's #StatesOfPride 50 young people from across America shared with us what Pride means to them 🌈 #linkinbio

As you may know most of us a stuck at home due to COVID-19. During this social distancing I decided to do a bit of math to help my fellow teens. For many teens that feel they will never be with the person they like I have some math to show you. The world’s population is 7.8 billion which is a lot.
